## Why This Is Asked

This problem tests the ability to formulate a DP solution over prefixes with a partition constraint, combining range-based computations (maximum values) with block length considerations. It requires clear state definition, proper transition logic, and a strategy for reconstructing the solution from computed results.

## Key Concepts

- Dynamic programming over array prefixes and block count parameters
- State transitions focusing on the last block contribution
- Efficient handling of range maximum queries during transitions
- Solution reconstruction using parent pointers or backtracking
- Time-space trade-offs and potential RMQ-based optimizations

## Code Example

```javascript
// DP framework structure
function partitionArray(A, k) {
  const n = A.length;
  const dp = Array(n+1).fill().map(() => Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  const par = Array(n+1).fill().map(() => Array(k+1).fill(-1));

  // Base cases: single block
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    const maxVal = Math.max(...A.slice(0, i));
    dp[i][1] = maxVal * i;
  }

  // Fill DP table
  for (let t = 2; t <= k; t++) {
    for (let i = t; i <= n; i++) {
      for (let j = t-1; j < i; j++) {
        const maxLast = Math.max(...A.slice(j, i));
        const val = dp[j][t-1] + maxLast * (i-j);
        if (val > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = val;
          par[i][t] = j;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  // Reconstruct blocks
  const blocks = [];
  let curr = n, blocksLeft = k;
  while (blocksLeft > 0) {
    const start = par[curr][blocksLeft];
    blocks.push([start, curr-1]);
    curr = start;
    blocksLeft--;
  }

  return { value: dp[n][k], blocks: blocks.reverse() };
}
```

