We use a DP over the number of steps: let dp[v][i] represent the maximum total weight to reach vertex v using exactly i edges. We also maintain a parent array par[v][i] to store the predecessor node for path reconstruction.

**Initialization:** dp[s][0] = 0 (starting at s with zero edges traversed), and all other entries are set to -∞ (indicating unreachable states).

**Recurrence:** For each step i from 0 to k-1, iterate through all edges (u, v, w). If dp[u][i] is reachable, we can extend the walk to v:

dp[v][i+1] = max(dp[v][i+1], dp[u][i] + w)

We also record the predecessor: par[v][i+1] = u.

**Result:** After processing all k steps, the maximum total weight is dp[t][k]. To reconstruct the path, backtrack from t using the par array starting at step k.

**Time Complexity:** O(k · (n + m)) — we iterate through all edges k times.
**Space Complexity:** O(n · k) — storing the DP table and parent pointers.

**Code Example**

```javascript
function maxWalk(n, edges, s, t, k) {
  const INF = -1e15;
  const dp = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(INF));
  const par = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));

  dp[s][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 0; i < k; i++) {
    for (const [u, v, w] of edges) {
      if (dp[u][i] > INF) {
        const newWeight = dp[u][i] + w;
        if (newWeight > dp[v][i + 1]) {
          dp[v][i + 1] = newWeight;
          par[v][i + 1] = u;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  if (dp[t][k] === INF) return null;

  const path = [];
  let curr = t;
  for (let i = k; i > 0; i--) {
    path.unshift(curr);
    curr = par[curr][i];
  }
  path.unshift(s);

  return { weight: dp[t][k], path };
}
```

