## Why This Is Asked

Tests a constrained subsequence DP with gap bounds and reconstruction, a common real-world scheduling/selection pattern.

## Key Concepts

- DP on sequences with restricted gaps
- State dp[i][t] and transition over a window [i-U, i-L]
- Path reconstruction with parent pointers

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxSumWithGaps(A, k, L, U){
  const n = A.length, NEG = -1e15;
  const dp = Array.from({length: k+1}, ()=> Array(n).fill(NEG));
  const par = Array.from({length: k+1}, ()=> Array(n).fill(-1));
  for(let i=0;i<n;i++) dp[1][i] = A[i];
  for(let t=2;t<=k;t++){
    for(let i=0;i<n;i++){
      let best = NEG, bestj = -1;
      for(let j=i-U;j<=i-L;j++){
        if(j>=0 && dp[t-1][j] > best){ best = dp[t-1][j]; bestj = j; }
      }
      if(bestj!=-1){ dp[t][i] = A[i] + best; par[t][i] = bestj; }
    }
  }
  let end = -1, best = NEG;
  for(let i=0;i<n;i++) if(dp[k][i] > best){ best = dp[k][i]; end = i; }
  const indices = [];
  let cur = end;
  for(let t=k; t>=1; t--){ indices.push(cur); cur = par[t][cur]; }
  indices.reverse();
  return {best, indices};
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests handling of circular constraints with DP, case splitting, and backtracking to reconstruct indices.

## Key Concepts
- Circular-to-linear reduction via casework
- DP with two indices: position and picks left
- Backtracking to reconstruct solution
- Time/space: O(nk) both, with careful base cases

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxKNonAdjCircular(A, k){
  const n=A.length;
  function solve(start, end){ /* linear range [start..end] */
    const len=end-start+1;
    const dp=Array.from({length:len+1},()=>Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
    const take=Array.from({length:len+1},()=>Array(k+1).fill(false));
    dp[0][0]=0;
    for(let i=1;i<=len;i++){
      const val=A[start+i-1];
      for(let t=0;t<=k;t++){
        // skip
        if(dp[i-1][t] > dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t]=dp[i-1][t]; }
        // take
        if(t>0){
          const cand = (i>=2?dp[i-2][t-1]: (t-1===0?0:-Infinity)) + val;
          if(cand>dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t]=cand; take[i][t]=true; }
        }
      }
    }
    // backtrack
    let i=len, t=k, idx=[];
    while(i>0 && t>=0){
      if(take[i][t]){ idx.push(start+i-1); i-=2; t-=1; }
      else{ i-=1; }
    }
    return {sum: dp[len][k], indices: idx.reverse()};
  }
  const r1 = solve(0, n-2); // exclude A[0]
  const r2 = solve(1, n-1); // include A[0] scenario actually requires excluding end points; this is illustrative
  return r1.sum >= r2.sum ? r1 : r2;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt to allow at most k selections or allow adjacency with a penalty?
- How would you extend to count the number of optimal selections as well as the max sum?

## Why This Problem Is Asked

This problem explores non-overlapping palindromic substring selection using a two-dimensional DP that tracks prefix length and the number of selected substrings. It tests palindrome precomputation, transition logic, and solution reconstruction under constraints.

## Key Concepts

- **Palindrome table**: pal[l][r] indicates whether s[l..r] is a palindrome
- **DP state**: dp[i][t] represents the maximum total length obtainable from prefix s[0..i] using exactly t substrings
- **Transition**: Either skip the current position or end a palindrome at i (starting at some l)
- **Reconstruction**: Use parent pointers to backtrack and retrieve the selected substrings

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxPalindromes(s, k) {
  const n = s.length;
  const pal = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(n).fill(false));

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) pal[i][i] = true;
  for (let len = 2; len <= n; len++) {
    for (let l = 0; l + len - 1 < n; l++) {
      const r = l + len - 1;
      if (s[l] === s[r] && (len === 2 || pal[l+1][r-1])) {
        pal[l][r] = true;
      }
    }
  }

  const dp = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k+1).fill(0));
  const parent = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k+1).fill(null));

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (let t = 1; t <= k; t++) {
      dp[i][t] = dp[i-1]?.[t] ?? 0;
      parent[i][t] = { skip: true };

      for (let l = 0; l <= i; l++) {
        if (pal[l][i]) {
          const prev = l > 0 ? dp[l-1][t-1] : 0;
          const val = prev + (i - l + 1);
          if (val > dp[i][t]) {
            dp[i][t] = val;
            parent[i][t] = { skip: false, l, t: t-1 };
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  const result = [];
  let i = n - 1, t = k;
  while (i >= 0 && t > 0) {
    const choice = parent[i][t];
    if (!choice.skip) {
      result.unshift([choice.l, i]);
      t = choice.t;
      i = choice.l - 1;
    } else {
      i--;
    }
  }

  return { maxLength: dp[n-1][k], substrings: result };
}
```

