## Why This Is Asked
This tests modeling of selecting multiple disjoint subarrays with a fixed cost and a cap on count, including interval reconstruction. It blends standard DP on subarrays with a knapsack-like limit and requires careful state design.

## Key Concepts
- DP over prefix index i and subarray count t
- Prefix sums for fast subarray sums
- Transitions: skip vs end-subarray
- Reconstruction via back-pointers; space/time trade-offs

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxKSubarrays(A, k, c) {
  const n = A.length;
  const pref = new Array(n+1).fill(0);
  for (let i=1;i<=n;i++) pref[i] = pref[i-1] + A[i-1];
  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  const par = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(null));
  dp[0][0] = 0;
  for (let i=1;i<=n;i++){
    for (let t=0;t<=k;t++){
      // skip i
      dp[i][t] = dp[i-1][t];
      par[i][t] = {type:'skip'};
      if (t>0){
        for (let L=1; L<=i; L++){
          const prev = dp[i-L][t-1];
          if (prev <= -Infinity/2) continue;
          const cand = prev + (pref[i]-pref[i-L]) - c;
          if (cand > dp[i][t]){
            dp[i][t] = cand;
            par[i][t] = {type:'end', end:i, len:L};
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
  // reconstruction would walk back from (n, argmax_t)
  return {maxValue: dp[n].reduce((a,b)=> Math.max(a,b), -Infinity)};
}
