## Why This Problem Is Asked
This classic problem evaluates your ability to design clean DP states for interval selection with reconstruction requirements. It strikes the right balance—accessible to beginners while effectively testing state structuring and backtracking skills.

## Key Concepts
- **dp[i][t]** manages selections across the first i elements with at most t subarrays
- **local[i][t]** distinguishes between extending an existing subarray and starting a new one
- Backtracking through the DP table to reconstruct segment boundaries

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxSumSubarrays(nums, k) {
    if (!nums.length || k <= 0) return { maxSum: 0, subarrays: [] };

    const n = nums.length;
    const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(0));
    const local = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(0));
    const endIdx = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));

    for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        for (let t = 1; t <= Math.min(k, i); t++) {
            local[i][t] = Math.max(
                local[i - 1][t] + nums[i - 1],
                dp[i - 1][t - 1] + nums[i - 1]
            );
            if (local[i][t] === dp[i - 1][t - 1] + nums[i - 1]) {
                endIdx[i][t] = i - 1;
            }
            dp[i][t] = dp[i - 1][t] >= local[i][t] ? dp[i - 1][t] : local[i][t];
        }
    }

    const subarrays = [];
    let j = n, t = k;
    while (t > 0 && j > 0) {
        if (endIdx[j][t] !== -1) {
            let start = endIdx[j][t];
            while (start > 0 && endIdx[start][t] !== -1) start--;
            subarrays.unshift([start, endIdx[j][t]]);
            j = start;
            t--;
        } else {
            break;
        }
    }

    return { maxSum: dp[n][k], subarrays };
}
```

