**DP Formulation:**

Define `dp[i][t]` as the minimum cost to select a subsequence of exactly `t` elements where the `t`th (last) element ends at index `i`. The cost represents the total variation of the selected subsequence.

**Base case:** `dp[i][1] = 0` for all `i`. When only one element is selected, there are no consecutive pairs, so the cost is zero.

**Transition:** For `t ≥ 2`:
```
dp[i][t] = min_{j < i} ( dp[j][t-1] + |A[i] - A[j]| )
```
This transition considers all valid previous positions `j` and adds the cost of moving from `A[j]` to `A[i]`.

**Parent pointers:** Store `parent[i][t] = argmin_j` to reconstruct the chosen indices via backtracking.

**Result:** The minimum total variation is `min_i dp[i][k]`. Reconstruct the indices by backtracking from the index `i` that achieves this minimum.

**Complexity:** O(n²·k) time, O(n·k) space.

---

**Code Example:**
```javascript
function minCostSubseq(A, k) {
  const n = A.length;
  const dp = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(Infinity));
  const parent = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[i][1] = 0;

  for (let t = 2; t <= k; t++) {
    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
        const cost = dp[j][t - 1] + Math.abs(A[i] - A[j]);
        if (cost < dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = cost;
          parent[i][t] = j;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  let minCost = Infinity, endIdx = -1;
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (dp[i][k] < minCost) {
      minCost = dp[i][k];
      endIdx = i;
    }
  }

  const indices = [];
  let cur = endIdx;
  for (let t = k; t >= 1; t--) {
    indices.unshift(cur);
    cur = parent[cur][t];
  }

  return { minCost, indices };
}
```

