## Why This Is Asked
Tests DP on subsequences with transition costs; requires deriving a 2D DP with O(n^2 m) time and backpointers. Edge cases: m=1 yields 0. Consider tie-breaking on reconstruction.

## Key Concepts
- DP on subsequences; 2D states; O(n^2 m) time; backtracking via parents; rolling arrays for space.

## Code Example
```javascript
function minCostSubseq(A, m){
  const n = A.length;
  const INF = 1e18;
  const dp = Array.from({length: n}, ()=>Array(m+1).fill(INF));
  const par = Array.from({length: n}, ()=>Array(m+1).fill(-1));
  for(let i=0; i<n; i++) dp[i][1] = 0;
  for(let i=0; i<n; i++){
    for(let t=2; t<=m; t++){
      for(let p=0; p<i; p++){
        const val = dp[p][t-1] + Math.abs(A[i]-A[p]);
        if(val < dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t] = val; par[i][t] = p; }
      }
    }
  }
  let best = INF, end = -1;
  for(let i=0; i<n; i++){ if(dp[i][m] < best){ best = dp[i][m]; end = i; } }
  const idx = []; let t=m, cur = end;
  while(t >= 1){ idx.push(cur); cur = par[cur][t]; t--; }
  idx.reverse();
  return {cost: best, indices: idx};
}
```

## Why This Problem Is Asked
This problem evaluates understanding of weighted interval scheduling with a cardinality constraint—a fundamental DP pattern in scheduling and resource allocation. It also tests the ability to reconstruct the actual solution, not just compute the optimal value.

## Key Concepts
- Weighted interval scheduling with an exact cardinality constraint
- Precomputing p(i) via binary search after sorting intervals by their right endpoint
- Two-dimensional DP table indexed by interval position and number selected
- Backtracking through the DP table to recover the chosen intervals

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxValueWithKIntervals(intervals, A, k) {
    intervals.sort((a, b) => a.r - b.r);
    const n = intervals.length;
    const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(0));
    const selected = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(false));

    for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        const [l, r] = [intervals[i-1].l, intervals[i-1].r];
        const v = intervals[i-1].value;
        const p = findPrev(intervals, i-1);

        for (let t = 1; t <= k; t++) {
            if (dp[p][t-1] + v > dp[i-1][t]) {
                dp[i][t] = dp[p][t-1] + v;
                selected[i][t] = true;
            } else {
                dp[i][t] = dp[i-1][t];
            }
        }
    }

    const result = [];
    let i = n, t = k;
    while (i > 0 && t > 0) {
        if (selected[i][t]) {
            result.unshift(i - 1);
            t--;
            i = p;
        } else {
            i--;
        }
    }

    return { maxValue: dp[n][k], indices: result };
}

function findPrev(intervals, idx) {
    let lo = 0, hi = idx;
    while (lo < hi) {
        const mid = Math.ceil((lo + hi) / 2);
        if (intervals[mid].r <= intervals[idx].l) lo = mid;
        else hi = mid - 1;
    }
    return lo;
}
```

## Complexity Analysis
- Preprocessing p(i): O(n log n) via sorting and binary search
- DP computation: O(n × k)
- Reconstruction: O(n + k)
- Space: O(n × k) for the DP table

## Why This Is Asked
Offers a new DP angle: path with exact turns, combining grid path DP with turn accounting. Tests deriving a tight state space, base cases, and reconstruction, mirroring routing-like constraints in real systems.

## Key Concepts
- Grid DP with an extra dimension for turns
- Two direction states to capture turns
- Reconstruction via backpointers
- Careful base/edge-case handling (start cell, negative infinities)

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxPathWithTurns(grid, K) {
  const n = grid.length, m = grid[0].length;
  const NEG = -Infinity;
  // 4D DP: [i][j][t][d]
  const dp = Array.from({length: n}, () => Array.from({length: m}, () =>
    Array.from({length: K+1}, () => [NEG, NEG])));
  dp[0][0][0][0] = grid[0][0];
  dp[0][0][0][1] = grid[0][0];
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < m; j++) {
      for (let t = 0; t <= K; t++) {
        if (i === 0 && j === 0) continue;
        // last move right
        if (j > 0) {
          dp[i][j][t][0] = Math.max(
            (dp[i][j-1][t][0] !== NEG ? dp[i][j-1][t][0] : NEG),
            (t > 0 && dp[i-1][j][t-1][1] !== NEG ? dp[i-1][j][t-1][1] : NEG)
          ) + grid[i][j];
        }
        // last move down
        if (i > 0) {
          dp[i][j][t][1] = Math.max(
            (dp[i-1][j][t][1] !== NEG ? dp[i-1][j][t][1] : NEG),
            (t > 0 && dp[i][j-1][t-1][0] !== NEG ? dp[i][j-1][t-1][0] : NEG)
          ) + grid[i][j];
        }
      }
    }
  }
  return Math.max(dp[n-1][m-1][K][0], dp[n-1][m-1][K][1]);
}
```

