## Why This Is Asked
This question tests building a DP over subsequences with constraints, requiring a clear state definition and transition over previous indices, plus reconstruction capabilities.

## Key Concepts
- Subsequence DP with constraints
- State dp[i] and parent tracking
- Time/space analysis and reconstruction

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxSubseqWithDiff(a, d) {
  const n = a.length;
  const dp = Array(n).fill(0);
  const par = Array(n).fill(-1);
  let best = -Infinity, bestIdx = -1;

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    dp[i] = a[i];
    for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
      if (Math.abs(a[i] - a[j]) <= d && dp[j] + a[i] > dp[i]) {
        dp[i] = dp[j] + a[i];
        par[i] = j;
      }
    }
    if (dp[i] > best) {
      best = dp[i];
      bestIdx = i;
    }
  }

  // Reconstruct subsequence
  const seq = [];
  let curr = bestIdx;
  while (curr !== -1) {
    seq.push(curr);
    curr = par[curr];
  }
  return { maxSum: best, subsequence: seq.reverse() };
}
```

## Time/Space Complexity
Time: O(n²) due to nested loops checking all previous indices
Space: O(n) for dp and parent arrays

## Why This Is Asked
Advanced DP with fixed-step paths and path reconstruction, mirroring typical Stripe/Robinhood interview patterns where you optimize over constrained moves and require traceable decisions.

## Key Concepts
- DP state as position and step count (pos, m)
- Transition with +1 or +2 jumps
- Path reconstruction via parent pointers
- Time/space complexity trade-offs

## Code Example
```javascript
// DP skeleton (rewards length n, k moves)
function maxReward(rewards, k){
  const n = rewards.length;
  const a = rewards.concat(0);
  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  const par = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => Array(k+1).fill(null));
  dp[0][0] = a[0];
  for(let m=0; m<k; m++){
    for(let pos=0; pos<=n; pos++){
      if(dp[pos][m] === -Infinity) continue;
      if(pos+1 <= n){
        const val = dp[pos][m] + a[pos+1];
        if(val > dp[pos+1][m+1]){ dp[pos+1][m+1] = val; par[pos+1][m+1] = [pos, m, 1]; }
      }
      if(pos+2 <= n){
        const val = dp[pos][m] + a[pos+2];
        if(val > dp[pos+2][m+1]){ dp[pos+2][m+1] = val; par[pos+2][m+1] = [pos, m, 2]; }
      }
    }
  }
  // reconstruct path (omitted for brevity in snippet)
  return {best: dp[n][k]};
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt if end position is not fixed? 
- How to optimize memory to O(nk) -> O(n) using rolling arrays?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests DP over non-overlapping intervals with a fixed per-interval cost, including reconstruction. It probes prefix-sum optimization and careful state transitions.

## Key Concepts
- DP over non-overlapping subarrays with exact k blocks
- Prefix sums to compute subarray sums in O(1)
- Optimizing inner max to achieve O(nk) runtime

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxKSubarrays(A, k, c){
  const n = A.length;
  const P = new Array(n+1).fill(0);
  for(let i=1;i<=n;i++) P[i] = P[i-1] + A[i-1];
  const dp = Array.from({length:n+1}, ()=> new Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  for(let i=0;i<=n;i++) dp[i][0] = 0;
  for(let t=1;t<=k;t++){
    let best = -Infinity; let bestL = -1;
    for(let i=1;i<=n;i++){
      dp[i][t] = dp[i-1][t];
      if(best !== -Infinity){
        dp[i][t] = Math.max(dp[i][t], best + P[i] - c);
      }
      const cand = dp[i-1][t-1] - P[i-1];
      if(cand > best){ best = cand; bestL = i; }
    }
  }
  // Reconstruction would backtrack using a separate trace array (omitted for brevity)
  return dp[n][k];
}
```

## Problem Context
This problem extends the classic k-segment DP by adding segment length bounds, testing proficiency with multi-dimensional state management, careful index handling, and segment reconstruction.

## Key Concepts
- 2D DP over position (i) and segment count (t)
- Prefix sums for O(1) segment value retrieval
- Backpointer storage for reconstructing optimal segment endpoints

## Solution Approach
Let P be the prefix sums array where P[i] = sum(A[1..i]). Define dp[i][t] as the maximum total value obtainable from the first i elements using exactly t segments. The recurrence is:

dp[i][t] = max(dp[i-1][t], max_{L ≤ len ≤ R} dp[i-len][t-1] + (P[i] - P[i-len]))

Base case: dp[0][0] = 0; all other entries initialized to -∞. Store backpointers during computation to reconstruct the optimal segment endpoints.

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxKSegments(A, k, L, R) {
  const n = A.length;
  const P = new Array(n + 1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) P[i] = P[i - 1] + A[i - 1];
  const NEG = -Infinity;
  const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(NEG));
  const back = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(null));
  dp[0][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (let t = 1; t <= k; t++) {
      for (let len = L; len <= R && len <= i; len++) {
        const prev = i - len;
        const val = dp[prev][t - 1] + (P[i] - P[prev]);
        if (val > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = val;
          back[i][t] = { len, prev };
        }
      }
      dp[i][t] = Math.max(dp[i][t], dp[i - 1][t]);
    }
  }

  const segments = [];
  let i = n, t = k;
  while (t > 0 && back[i][t]) {
    const { len, prev } = back[i][t];
    segments.push([prev + 1, i]);
    i = prev;
    t--;
  }
  return { value: dp[n][k], segments: segments.reverse() };
}
```

**Complexity**: O(n × k × R) time, O(n × k) space.

## Why This Is Asked
This problem tests advanced tree DP skills combined with a global size constraint (exactly k nodes) and requires reconstructing the selected subtree—both hallmarks of challenging interview problems.

## Key Concepts
- **Knapsack-style merges:** Combining child DPs mirrors the classic knapsack problem, requiring careful iteration order (typically iterate s in reverse to avoid reusing a child).
- **Connected-subtree constraint:** By defining DP to always include the current node, connectivity is guaranteed—subtrees remain connected through their parent.
- **Reconstruction:** Storing decision metadata (`choice`) enables backtracking without re-running DP.
- **Complexity:** O(n·k²) time with optimization potential to O(n·k) using convex hull tricks or similar techniques for large k.

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxConnectedSubtree(n, k, edges, w) {
  const g = Array.from({ length: n }, () => []);
  for (const [u, v] of edges) {
    g[u].push(v);
    g[v].push(u);
  }

  const parent = new Array(n).fill(-1);
  const order = [];
  const stack = [0];
  while (stack.length) {
    const u = stack.pop();
    order.push(u);
    for (const v of g[u]) {
      if (v !== parent[u]) {
        parent[v] = u;
        stack.push(v);
      }
    }
  }

  const best = Array.from({ length: n }, () => new Array(k + 1).fill(-Infinity));
  const choice = Array.from({ length: n }, () => new Array(k + 1).fill(null));

  for (const u of order.reverse()) {
    best[u][1] = w[u];
    for (const v of g[u]) {
      if (v === parent[u]) continue;
      for (let s = k; s >= 1; s--) {
        if (best[u][s] < 0) continue;
        for (let t = 1; t + s <= k; t++) {
          if (best[v][t] < 0) continue;
          const ns = s + t;
          const val = best[u][s] + best[v][t];
          if (val > best[u][ns]) {
            best[u][ns] = val;
            choice[u][ns] = { keep: s, from: { node: v, size: t } };
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  let root = 0;
  let bestVal = best[0][k];
  for (let u = 1; u < n; u++) {
    if (best[u][k] > bestVal) {
      bestVal = best[u][k];
      root = u;
    }
  }

  const selected = new Set();
  const reconstruct = (u, s) => {
    selected.add(u);
    if (s === 1) return;
    const c = choice[u][s];
    reconstruct(c.from.node, c.from.size);
    const inner = (node, parent) => {
      for (const v of g[node]) {
        if (v !== parent) inner(v, node);
      }
    };
  };
  reconstruct(root, k);

  return { maxWeight: bestVal, nodes: [...selected] };
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a DP with partitioning and additive segment costs; uses prefix sums to optimize the transition to O(nk).

## Key Concepts

- DP on partitioning into k segments
- Prefix sums to compute segment costs in O(1)
- State transition optimization with a running max and backpointers
- Reconstruction of cut points

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxPartitionScore(A, k){
  const n = A.length;
  if (k <= 0 || k > n) return {score: 0, cuts: []};
  const diff = new Array(n-1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 0; i < n-1; i++) diff[i] = Math.abs(A[i+1] - A[i]);
  const pref = new Array(n).fill(0);
  for (let i = 1; i < n; i++) pref[i] = pref[i-1] + diff[i-1];
  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => new Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  const take = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => new Array(k+1).fill(-1));
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) dp[i][1] = pref[i-1];
  for (let t = 2; t <= k; t++) {
    let best = -Infinity, bestP = -1;
    for (let i = t; i <= n; i++) {
      const p = i - 1;
      const val = dp[p][t-1] - pref[p];
      if (val > best) { best = val; bestP = p; }
      dp[i][t] = pref[i-1] + best;
      take[i][t] = bestP;
    }
  }
  let cuts = [];
  let i = n, t = k;
  while (t > 0) {
    const p = take[i][t];
    cuts.push(i);
    i = p;
    t--;
  }
  cuts.reverse();
  return {score: dp[n][k], cuts};
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests a less-traveled DP angle: maximizing a sum of subarray-specific statistics (distinct counts) with exact segmentation. Requires careful state design and backtracking for reconstruction.

## Key Concepts
- DP over prefix end i and segment count t
- Subarray distinct counts D(p,i-1)
- Backpointers for reconstruction
- Time: O(n^2 k), Space: O(nk)

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxDistinctPartition(A, k) {
  const n = A.length;
  // Precompute distinct counts D[l][r]
  const D = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(n).fill(0));
  for (let l = 0; l < n; l++) {
    const seen = new Set();
    for (let r = l; r < n; r++) {
      seen.add(A[r]);
      D[l][r] = seen.size;
    }
  }
  const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-Infinity));
  const bt = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) dp[i][1] = D[0][i - 1];
  for (let t = 2; t <= k; t++) {
    for (let i = t; i <= n; i++) {
      for (let p = t - 1; p <= i - 1; p++) {
        const cand = dp[p][t - 1] + D[p][i - 1];
        if (cand > dp[i][t]) { dp[i][t] = cand; bt[i][t] = p; }
      }
    }
  }
  // reconstruct
  let i = n, t = k;
  const segs = [];
  while (t > 0) {
    const p = bt[i][t];
    segs.push([p, i - 1]);
    i = p; t--;
  }
  segs.reverse();
  return { best: dp[n][k], segments: segs };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you optimize to O(nk) memory?
- How would you handle at most k segments instead of exactly k?
- Can you adapt to streaming data or reconstruct segments efficiently for large n?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests DP over subsequences with a fixed length and pairwise costs, plus explicit reconstruction. It moves beyond contiguous partitions by requiring last-step linkage through prior picks.

## Key Concepts
- Subsequence DP with fixed length
- Min-over-predecessor recurrence
- Path reconstruction via parent pointers
- Time/space trade-offs and practical optimizations

## Code Example
```javascript
function solve(A, m){
  const n=A.length;
  const dp=Array.from({length:n},()=>Array(m+1).fill(Infinity));
  const par=Array.from({length:n},()=>Array(m+1).fill(-1));
  for(let i=0;i<n;i++) dp[i][1]=0;
  for(let t=2;t<=m;t++){
    for(let i=t-1;i<n;i++){
      for(let j=t-2;j<i;j++){
        const c=dp[j][t-1]+Math.abs(A[i]-A[j]);
        if(c<dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t]=c; par[i][t]=j; }
      }
    }
  }
  let best=Infinity,bestI=-1;
  for(let i=m-1;i<n;i++){ if(dp[i][m]<best){ best=dp[i][m]; bestI=i; } }
  const path=[];
  let cur=bestI, t=m;
  while(t>=1){
    path.push(cur);
    cur=par[cur][t];
    t--;
  }
  path.reverse();
  return {cost:best, indices:path};
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests DP over prefixes with a non-linear subarray cost (max) and requires reconstruction.

## Key Concepts
- DP over prefixes and partition count
- On-the-fly max for subarray cost
- Reconstruction via prev pointers
- Time/space trade-offs (O(n^2 k) time, O(nk) space)

## Code Example
```javascript
function minCostPartition(A, k){
  const n = A.length;
  const INF = 1e15;
  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(INF));
  const prev = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(-1));
  dp[0][0] = 0;
  for(let i=1; i<=n; i++){
    for(let t=1; t<=Math.min(i,k); t++){
      let curMax = -Infinity;
      for(let p=i-1; p>=t-1; p--){
        curMax = Math.max(curMax, A[p]);
        const val = dp[p][t-1] + curMax;
        if(val < dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t] = val; prev[i][t] = p; }
      }
    }
  }
  return {cost: dp[n][k], prev};
}
```

